<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-624-739  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 624 739.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Nov 20 1990 v4 n40 p5(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Macweek 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Symantec cuts back on MORE development. (Symantec Corp's MOREoutlining and desktop presentation package)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gore, Andrew.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Symantec Corp. (Products).andO;Ticker:    SYMC.andO;Product:   More (Presentation software) (Product discontinuation).andO;Topic:     Product DiscontinuationSalesPresentation Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Symantec cuts back on MORE developmentandM;Cupertino, Calif.andP;  -- Symantec Corp. has canceled development of furtherversions of its MORE outlining and desktop presentation package because ofthe product's lackluster sales growth, according to an internal memo.andM;MORE has not demonstrated significant revenue growth in the past two years,despite substantial investment, the memo said.andP;  Symantec, based here,acquired the program in 1987 as part of a merger with Living Video-text Inc.,andO;the original developer of MORE and its predecessor, ThinkTank.andP;  The mostrecent upgrade, MORE 3.0, appeared in April.andM;&quot;From my perspective, this development is not at all surprising,&quot; said PeterRogers, senior analyst with Robertson, Stephens andamp; Co., a San Francisco-basedinvestment banking company that follows Symantec.andP;  &quot;MORE is in this nebulouscategory of idea processing, a category that has been extremely difficult tomarket.&quot;andM;Although Symantec will stop MORE development immediately, enough businessexists for the company to profit from MORE sales for another two years, thememo said.andP;  This profit will be contributed to other projects with &quot;highgrowth&quot; potential, according to the document.andM;&quot;Symantec probably will continue to supply residual demand, but by the end ofnext year [MORE] will be a nonentity at the company,&quot; Rogers predicted.andP;  &quot;Asfar as Wall Street is concerned, it's already a nonentity.&quot;andM;David Whitney, director of Symantec's business communications group, did notdeny MORE development cutbacks, but he did say the company would continue tosupport its customers with interim releases.andO;</TEXT></DOC>